         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot Garden ¶ 15. April 1858 ¶ My dear Sir William. ¶  ¶ We are again disappointed in not receiving our home letters, due before the despatch of the English mail, and I have therefore few rem...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">58.04.15</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To William Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Directors' letters, vol. LXXIV, Australia letters 1851-8, letter no. 177.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot Garden</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">15. April 1858</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir William.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>We are again disappointed in not receiving our home letters, due before the despatch of the English mail, and I have therefore few remark to offer by this steamer.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I beg to say, that your plants, sent per "Norfolk" are prospering. I bought a copy of Flora Tasmanica, which happened to be for sale at Hobarton, and am now at last in possession of fasc IV of this valuable work.<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker (1860). Fascicle IV was published on 28 July 1857 (TL2).</p>
               </note> From a hasty glance I am convinced, that I have to contribute not only many additional notes to the <name key="Coralliflorae">Coralliflorae</name>, but also several species and I commence this time with <name key="Limnanthemum%20exiguum">Limnanthemum exiguum</name>, <name key="Sebaea%20albidiflora">Sebaea albidiflora</name> &amp;c Mr Oldfields new researches in the S W. of V.D.L.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Van Diemen's Land (Tasmania).</p>
               </note> prove the occurrence of the [Genus] <name key="Gingidium">Gingidium</name> there,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Presumably <seg style="font-style: italic; ">G. procumbens</seg> (B58.03.01, p. 15).</p>
               </note> which again produces an [edemic] species. Some new notes on <name key="Epacridae">Epacridae</name> I hope to supply by next mail. It is quite evident, that Dr Hooker had in many instances to contend with imperfect material, and I believe to be in the position to prove, that many reductions in the species are again necessary. In the pharmac. journal, which I have the pleasure to forward, I described the new <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Rhus</hi>
               </seg> rhodanthemum,<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B58.04.01, p. 43.</p>
               </note> like your South African one, it is decandrous.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <name key="Leucopogon%20affinis">Leucopogon affinis</name> is an excellent species and ranges as far as Moreton Bay! but grows not in South Australia, altho in Victoria, N.S. Wales &amp; Tasmania. —</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have written to Mr Pamplin to send me as soon as possible the new edition of Steudel Nomenclator Botanicus<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Steudel (1840-1).</p>
               </note> which would be very useful for my compiling the new catalogue of the garden. A second hand copy of Bot. Magaz. &amp; Bot. Regist.<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Curtis (1787-1800), Sims (1810-26) <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and W. Hooker (1827-64); <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>S. Edwards (1815-28), Lindley (1829-47).</p>
               </note> would be also the most powerful aid in my labours I could have.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I intend to devote my spare hours for a few months to the genus Eucalyptus. If any duplicates of this genus authentically named were obtainable anywhere, it would be indeed a great aid. </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I hope my letter per last mail reached your friend Ch. Darwin.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">In reply to C. Darwin to M, 8 December 1857; see M to C. Darwin, March 1858 (in this edition as 58-03-00c). Lucas (2010), pp. 103–4, <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>shows that the citation in Darwin's manuscript now published as Stauffer (1975), p. 553, did not, as Burkhardt <seg style="font-style: italic; ">et al</seg>. (1985–), vol. 8, p. 501 infer, come from this letter.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Wishing you all prosperity</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am, dear Sir William, </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your humble</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Eucalyptus [R]isdoni is certainly only a young state of an alternately leaved Eucalyptus!<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Joseph Hooker described <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Eucalyptus%20risdoni">Eucalyptus risdoni</name>
                     </seg> in J. Hooker (1847), p. 477.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The genus <name key="Maundia">Maundia</name> occurs in my North Austr. collection as <name key="Leiostigma">Leiostigma</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Maundia">Maundia</name>
                     </seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">M. triglochinoides</seg>) in B58.03.01, p 23; it had been distributed as '<seg style="">
                        <name key="Leiostigma">Leiostigma</name> (ng) troglochinoides' collected at Brisbane River: see K 98531. That sheet, and sheets MEL 2057296 and MEL 2057297, also carry the name Triglochin maundii, a name given provisionally in B67.12.01, p. 83.</seg>
                  </p>
                  <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
               </note> a name which is not very characteristic in <name key="Juncagineae">Juncagineae</name>.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
